The problem requires finding a lower bound for \(P(|Y / n - 0.25| < 0.05)\) when \(Y \sim b(n, 0.25)\) and \(n = 500\).

Using Chebyshev's inequality, for a random variable \(X\) with mean \(\mu\) and variance \(\sigma^2\), \(P(|X - \mu| \geq d) \leq \sigma^2 / d^2\). Thus, \(P(|X - \mu| < d) \geq 1 - \sigma^2 / d^2\).

Here, \(X = Y / n\), so \(\mu = p = 0.25\) and \(\sigma^2 = \text{Var}(Y / n) = p(1 - p) / n\). For \(n = 500\) and \(p = 0.25\):
\[
\sigma^2 = \frac{0.25 \times 0.75}{500} = \frac{0.1875}{500} = 0.000375.
\]
