Problem: Extend Example 1.4-6 to an $n$-sided die. That is, suppose that a fair $n$-sided die is rolled $n$ independent times. A match occurs if side $i$ is observed on the $i$ th trial, $i=1,2, \ldots, n$. Find the limit of this probability as $n$ increases without bound. The unit of the answer should be  .
Solution: The problem involves finding the limit of the probability of at least one match when a fair $n$-sided die is rolled $n$ independent times, where a match occurs if side $i$ is observed on the $i$-th trial for $i = 1, 2, \ldots, n$. The probability of no match on any single trial is $(n-1)/n$, and since the rolls are independent, the probability of no matches at all is $[(n-1)/n]^n$. Therefore, the probability of at least one match is $1 - [(n-1)/n]^n$.

As $n$ approaches infinity, $[(n-1)/n]^n = (1 - 1/n)^n$ converges to $e^{-1} \approx 0.367879$. Thus, the limit of the probability is $1 - e^{-1} \approx 1 - 0.367879 = 0.632121$.

Rounded to three significant figures, this is $0.632$. The answer is unitless, as it is a probability.

