Problem: Calculate the energy of one mole of UV photons of wavelength $300 \mathrm{~nm}$ and compare it with a typical single-bond energy of $400 \mathrm{~kJ} / \mathrm{mol}$. The unit of the answer should be  $\mathrm{~kJ} / \mathrm{mol}$.
Solution: The energy of one mole of photons is calculated using the formula \( E = \frac{N_A h c}{\lambda} \), where \( N_A \) is Avogadro's number (\( 6.022 \times 10^{23} \, \text{mol}^{-1} \)), \( h \) is Planck's constant (\( 6.626 \times 10^{-34} \, \text{J} \cdot \text{s} \)), \( c \) is the speed of light (\( 3.00 \times 10^8 \, \text{m/s} \)), and \( \lambda \) is the wavelength (\( 300 \, \text{nm} = 3.00 \times 10^{-7} \, \text{m} \)).

