\[ E = \frac{(6.022 \times 10^{23}) \times (6.626 \times 10^{-34}) \times (3.00 \times 10^8)}{3.00 \times 10^{-7}} = 399,000 \, \text{J/mol} \]

Convert to kilojoules per mole:  
\[ 399,000 \, \text{J/mol} \div 1000 = 399 \, \text{kJ/mol} \]

The wavelength \( 300 \, \text{nm} \) has three significant figures, so the result is rounded to three significant figures, giving \( 399 \, \text{kJ/mol} \).

Comparison with the typical single-bond energy of \( 400 \, \text{kJ/mol} \) shows that the photon energy (\( 399 \, \text{kJ/mol} \)) is very close to the bond energy, indicating that UV light of this wavelength can potentially break such bonds.

