Problem: Calculate the magnitude of the spin angular momentum of a proton. Give a numerical answer.  The unit of the answer should be  $10^{-35} \mathrm{~J} \mathrm{~s}$.
Solution: The magnitude of the spin angular momentum for a proton, which has a spin quantum number \( s = \frac{1}{2} \), is given by \( \sqrt{s(s+1)} \hbar \). Substituting \( s = \frac{1}{2} \), the expression simplifies to \( \sqrt{\frac{1}{2} \times \frac{3}{2}} \hbar = \sqrt{\frac{3}{4}} \hbar = \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \hbar \).

Using \( \hbar \approx 1.0545718 \times 10^{-34} \, \text{J} \cdot \text{s} \) and \( \sqrt{3} \approx 1.7320508 \),  
\[ \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \approx 0.8660254, \]  
\[ 0.8660254 \times 1.0545718 \times 10^{-34} \approx 9.13286 \times 10^{-35} \, \text{J} \cdot \text{s}. \]

The result is approximately \( 9.13286 \times 10^{-35} \, \text{J} \cdot \text{s} \). In units of \( 10^{-35} \, \text{J} \cdot \text{s} \), the value is 9.13286. Rounding to three significant figures, which is reasonable given the precision of Planck's constant, gives 9.13.

