Problem: The positron has charge $+e$ and mass equal to the electron mass. Calculate in electronvolts the ground-state energy of positronium-an "atom" that consists of a positron and an electron. The unit of the answer should be $\mathrm{eV}$.
Solution: The ground-state energy of positronium is calculated based on the hydrogen-like atom model, accounting for the reduced mass. Since both the electron and positron have the same mass \(m_e\), the reduced mass \(\mu\) is \(\frac{m_e}{2}\). For hydrogen, the ground-state energy is \(-13.6 \, \text{eV}\) with reduced mass approximately \(m_e\). The energy scales linearly with the reduced mass, so for positronium:

\[
E_{\text{ps}} = \left( \frac{\mu_{\text{ps}}}{\mu_{\text{H}}} \right) E_{\text{H}} = \left( \frac{\frac{m_e}{2}}{m_e} \right) \times (-13.6 \, \text{eV}) = \frac{1}{2} \times (-13.6 \, \text{eV}) = -6.8 \, \text{eV}
\]

The value is rounded to three significant figures, consistent with the precision of the hydrogen ground-state energy (\(-13.6 \, \text{eV}\)).

